```java
public <T> T mock(Class<T> classToMock, MockSettings mockSettings, boolean shouldResetOngoingStubbing) { 
    return mock(classToMock, mockSettings); 
}
```

This method is ignoring the `shouldResetOngoingStubbing` parameter! It should respect this flag and reset the ongoing stubbing when it's true. Looking back at the first `mock` method:

```java
public <T> T mock(Class<T> classToMock, MockSettings mockSettings) {
    mockingProgress.validateState();
    mockingProgress.resetOngoingStubbing();  // This always resets!
    return mockUtil.createMock(classToMock, (MockSettingsImpl) mockSettings);
}
```

The issue is that the second `mock` method always calls `resetOngoingStubbing()`, but when creating a mock with RETURNS_MOCKS, it should preserve the ongoing stubbing state for nested mock creation.

Let me check the calling test again. The test creates a mock with `RETURNS_MOCKS`, then tries to call `when(mock.objectReturningMethodNoArgs()).thenReturn(null)`. From looking at the ReturnsMocks code, when `objectReturningMethodNoArgs()` is called, it will create another mock internally, and this creates a conflict with the ongoing stubbing mechanism.

