Perfect! Now I can see the problem clearly. When `mock(Class<T> classToMock, Answer defaultAnswer)` is called (as in `mock(IMethods.class, RETURNS_MOCKS)`), it calls:

```java
return mock(classToMock, withSettings().defaultAnswer(defaultAnswer));
```

Which eventually calls:

```java
return MOCKITO_CORE.mock(classToMock, mockSettings);
```

Which goes to this method in MockitoCore:

```java
public <T> T mock(Class<T> classToMock, MockSettings mockSettings) {
    mockingProgress.validateState();
    mockingProgress.resetOngoingStubbing();  // <-- THIS IS THE PROBLEM!
    return mockUtil.createMock(classToMock, (MockSettingsImpl) mockSettings);
}
```

The problem occurs when you have an ongoing stubbing (like when calling `when(...)`), and then inside that, a mock is being created with RETURNS_MOCKS. Since the mock creation resets the ongoing stubbing, it interferes with the ongoing stubbing process.

Looking again at the mock method that takes the boolean parameter:

```java
public <T> T mock(Class<T> classToMock, MockSettings mockSettings, boolean shouldResetOngoingStubbing) { 
    return mock(classToMock, mockSettings); 
}
```

This method ignores the `shouldResetOngoingStubbing` flag! It calls the other method which *always* resets the ongoing stubbing. But it should only reset if `shouldResetOngoingStubbing` is true.

